# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1924-washington-senators-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1901 Chicago White Stockings season** was their first season as a major league team, and their second season in Chicago.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] It was also the inaugural season of American League as a major league.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings had a very balanced lineup, which was led by outfielders Dummy Hoy and Fielder Jones, and scored the most runs in the AL.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] They relied primarily on speed, as Frank Isbell, Sam Mertes, and Jones finished 1–2–3 in stolen bases.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Clark Griffith, who went 24–7 with a 2.67 ERA.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The **1901 major league baseball season** was contested from April 18 through October 6, 1901.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural major league season for the American League (AL) (having previously been the minor league Western League), with the Chicago White Stockings winning the AL pennant.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Pittsburgh Pirates won the NL pennant.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of the modern era.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the only season in which the Milwaukee Brewers played, as the team would relocate to St.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, Missouri for the following season as the St.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns (before that team relocated to Baltimore, Maryland as the modern Baltimore Orioles in 1954, where they remain to this day.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles of this season would fold following the 1902 season).
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The 1901 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 18 with a game between the Brooklyn Superbas and the Philadelphia Phillies, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 24, with a game between the Chicago White Stockings and the Cleveland Bluebirds.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the season on September 28, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 6.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] On February 27, 1901, the National League Rules Committee announced several rule changes, effective immediately.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (8 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds would play their final game at League Park, on October 6 during a doubleheader against the St.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, moving into the Palace of the Fans for the start of the 1902 season.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-washington-senators-season] The 1901 Washington Senators won 61 games, lost 72, and finished in sixth place in the American League in its first year as a major league team.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1901-washington-senators-season] They were managed by Jim Manning and played home games at the American League Park I.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1902 Philadelphia Athletics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team finished first in the American League with a record of 83 wins and 53 losses.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] In 1902, the Philadelphia Phillies obtained an injunction, effective only in Pennsylvania, barring Athletics' second baseman Nap Lajoie from playing baseball for any team other than the Phillies.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Lajoie had played for the Athletics in 1901, and appeared in just one game in 1902 before the injunction went into effect.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The American League responded by transferring Lajoie's contract to the Cleveland Bronchos, who were subsequently known as the "Naps" in Lajoie's honor for several seasons.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Following the A's pennant winning season, the *Philadelphia Inquirer* organized a championship parade for the team through the city on Monday night, September 30, 1902.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team proceeded in open carriages and were reviewed by Philadelphia Mayor Ashbridge in front of the *Inquirer'*s building on Market Street.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] "There were more than 25,000 base ball enthusiasts from Philadelphia and nearly every town within a radius of twenty miles of the city in the parade.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] A thousand effigies of the "white elephant" were carried by the paraders.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] There were fifteen bands and twenty fife and drum corps in line to furnish music for the marchers." It was estimated that more than 200,000 turned out for the parade.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1902-washington-senators-season] The **1902 Washington Senators** won 61 games, lost 75, and finished in sixth place in the American League.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1902-washington-senators-season] They were managed by Tom Loftus and played home games at the American League Park I.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The **1903 Boston Americans season** was the third season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 91 wins and 47 losses, 14+1⁄2 games ahead of the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston went on to participate in the first World Series held between the AL and National League (NL) champions.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans won the 1903 World Series in eight games over the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Macon, Georgia.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Cy Young was a coach for the Mercer University baseball team, also based in Macon.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Boston Americans played an exhibition game against Mercer University (with Cy Young pitching for Mercer) on March 23; the outcome being a 13─2 victory for Boston.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest losing streak was three games, which occurred twice; April 20–23 and September 22–23.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest game was 12 innings, which occurred three times.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 13 home runs and had 104 RBIs, and Patsy Dougherty with a .331 batting average.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-boston-americans-season] It was Freeman's third consecutive season with at least 100 RBIs.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 40 appearances (35 starts) and pitched 34 complete games with a 28–9 record and 2.08 ERA, while striking out 176 in 341+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had two other 20-game winners; Bill Dinneen (21–13) and Tom Hughes (20–7).
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had three games end in a tie; July 31 at Washington, August 29 at Washington, and September 25 vs.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Tie games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tie games are counted.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston had an 11-game winning streak from May 28 through June 8, to put themselves in the AL lead.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-boston-americans-season] While they briefly fell into second place in mid-June, behind Philadelphia, Boston then won 9-of-10 to recapture the lead, which they held through the end of the season.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans met the Pittsburgh Pirates in the first modern World Series, an agreement between the AL and the NL as a post-season tournament.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The "Amerks" won the best-of-nine series in eight games; after falling behind, 3–1, they won four games in a row, clinching the championship at their home field, the Huntington Avenue Grounds, in Boston.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-washington-senators-season] The **1903 Washington Senators** won 43 games, lost 94, and finished in eighth place in the American League.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-washington-senators-season] Washington had finished in sixth place in each of the previous two seasons (the first two seasons of the American League's existence).
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-washington-senators-season] However, they fell to eighth and last in 1903.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-washington-senators-season] Their only star player, Big Ed Delahanty, got drunk and fell off a bridge into Niagara Falls midway through the season.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-washington-senators-season] The Senators' pitching had always been bad, and indeed, they would allow the most runs in the AL, but without Delahanty the offense sputtered to a halt.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1903-washington-senators-season] Their collective batting average was .231, bad even for the dead-ball era, and no one drove in more than 49 runs.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1924-washington-senators-season] The **1924 Washington Senators** won 92 games, lost 62, and finished in first place in the American League.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1924-washington-senators-season] Fueled by the excitement of winning their first AL pennant, the Senators won the World Series in dramatic fashion, a 12-inning Game 7 victory.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1924-washington-senators-season] The Senators' offense was led by future Hall of Famer Goose Goslin, who was one of the youngest players on the team.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1924-washington-senators-season] Walter Johnson had another outstanding year, winning the American League pitching Triple Crown and being voted Most Valuable Player.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1924-washington-senators-season] He anchored a staff that allowed the fewest runs in the league.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1924-washington-senators-season] Reliever Firpo Marberry paced the circuit in saves and games pitched.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1924-washington-senators-season] Manager Bucky Harris, who was also the team's starting second baseman, was the highest paid player on the team, earning $9,000.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1924-washington-senators-season] The Senators drew 584,310 fans to their 77 home games at Griffith Stadium, good for 4th place among the 8 American League teams and an average of 7,588 per game.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1924-washington-senators-season] Note: Firpo Marberry was team leader and MLB leader in saves with 15.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1924-washington-senators-season] The Senators finally made it into the postseason after many years of being the laughingstock of the American League.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1924-washington-senators-season] Behind ace pitcher Walter Johnson, they won the deciding Game Seven 4-3 in extra innings.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1924-washington-senators-season] The team returned to the World Series the next year and also in 1933, losing both, their last Series while playing in Washington.
[src:1924-washington-senators-season/1924-washington-senators-season] It wasn’t until 2019 that an MLB team based in the District of Columbia won another World Series.
